{"schema_version":"1","crate":"wikiada","version":"1.5.0","id":"b740a60d2e2a0c64","name":"Util.Http.Clients","qualified_name":"Util.Http.Clients","kind":"ada_package","location":{"file":"../../../home/runner/.local/share/alire/builds/utilada_2.8.2_30b22a59/4ad568c8d185b13a4b0f496912d263f14b692e0709f1ccf771a1531595b64c8f/src/sys/http/util-http-clients.ads","line":39,"column":9},"code":"package Util.Http.Clients","documentation":{"description":"== Client ==\nThe <tt>Util.Http.Clients</tt> package defines a set of API for an HTTP client to send\nrequests to an HTTP server.\n\n=== GET request ===\nTo retrieve a content using the HTTP GET operation, a client instance must be created.\nThe response is returned in a specific object that must therefore be declared:\n\n  Http     : Util.Http.Clients.Client;\n  Response : Util.Http.Clients.Response;\n\nBefore invoking the GET operation, the client can setup a number of HTTP headers.\n\n  Http.Add_Header (\"X-Requested-By\", \"wget\");\n\nThe GET operation is performed when the <tt>Get</tt> procedure is called:\n\n  Http.Get (\"http://www.google.com\", Response);\n\nOnce the response is received, the <tt>Response</tt> object contains the status of the\nHTTP response, the HTTP reply headers and the body.  A response header can be obtained\nby using the <tt>Get_Header</tt> function and the body using <tt>Get_Body</tt>:\n\n  Body : constant String := Response.Get_Body;"},"tagged_types":[{"id":"62b4a5d1b156c8e1","name":"Client","qualified_name":"Util.Http.Clients.Client","kind":"ada_tagged_type","location":{"file":"../../../home/runner/.local/share/alire/builds/utilada_2.8.2_30b22a59/4ad568c8d185b13a4b0f496912d263f14b692e0709f1ccf771a1531595b64c8f/src/sys/http/util-http-clients.ads","line":105,"column":9},"code":"type Client is limited new Abstract_Request with private;","progenitor_types":[{"qualified_name":"Util.Http.Abstract_Request","id":"d9f6f824e08c1760","unit":"util-http"}],"derived_types":[{"qualified_name":"Util.Http.Rest